00:04:36.370 --> 00:04:40.790
was talk about the definition
of the term sabermetrics.

00:04:40.790 --> 00:04:42.870
Sabermetrics has a funny origin.

00:04:42.870 --> 00:04:44.240
Here's the origin.

00:04:44.240 --> 00:04:46.440
The origin comes
from SABR, which

00:04:46.440 --> 00:04:49.670
is the Society for
American Baseball Research,

00:04:49.670 --> 00:04:55.830
and metrics is just a word to
say how to measure baseball.

00:04:55.830 --> 00:05:02.400
And so sabermetrics-- it's
only been a word since 1981.

00:05:02.400 --> 00:05:04.500
But Voltaire was
the first person

00:05:04.500 --> 00:05:09.500
to do this-- those of you who
are philosophers or readers.

00:05:09.500 --> 00:05:11.877
Voltaire said first
define your terms.

00:05:11.877 --> 00:05:12.960
And it's really important.

00:05:12.960 --> 00:05:14.570
When you look at
this definition,

00:05:14.570 --> 00:05:15.850
I'd say this is incorrect.

00:05:15.850 --> 00:05:18.390
This is not what
sabermetrics is.

00:05:18.390 --> 00:05:22.600
Sabermetrics is not the
statistical analysis

00:05:22.600 --> 00:05:23.900
of baseball data.

00:05:23.900 --> 00:05:27.180
That's way too
narrow a definition

00:05:27.180 --> 00:05:29.340
for what sabermetrics is.

00:05:29.340 --> 00:05:31.740
And like a good
scientist, I just

00:05:31.740 --> 00:05:36.100
want to show something and let
you see and think about this.

00:05:36.100 --> 00:05:39.480
This is slow motion of
a pitcher for the Red

00:05:39.480 --> 00:05:40.800
Sox named Daniel Bard.

00:05:40.800 --> 00:05:42.740
This is from 2010.

00:05:42.740 --> 00:05:44.870
And I say Daniel Bard
the Good, because this

00:05:44.870 --> 00:05:47.900
was a year where Daniel Bard
was pitching extremely well.

00:05:47.900 --> 00:05:49.980
For those of you who
are baseball fans,

00:05:49.980 --> 00:05:52.620
you may remember Daniel
Bard a few years ago

00:05:52.620 --> 00:05:57.020
and how great a pitcher he was
that one season especially.

00:05:57.020 --> 00:06:00.600
Now, if you pay attention to
these two slow motion videos,

00:06:00.600 --> 00:06:03.850
this is the same inning
in the same game.

00:06:03.850 --> 00:06:07.740
These are like
two pitches apart.

00:06:07.740 --> 00:06:09.600
A pitch count-- well,
three pitches apart.

00:06:09.600 --> 00:06:12.650
You can see the pitch
count on the top screen.

00:06:12.650 --> 00:06:14.990
The first on the left
is the Derek Jeter.

00:06:14.990 --> 00:06:16.420
It's at Yankee Stadium.

00:06:16.420 --> 00:06:19.120
And it's a fastball.

00:06:19.120 --> 00:06:21.810
And even though the physics--
we all know the physics

00:06:21.810 --> 00:06:25.480
say that the fastball
can't rise above gravity.

00:06:25.480 --> 00:06:27.390
If you appreciate
what's going on here,

00:06:27.390 --> 00:06:32.370
that fastball is defying gravity
by having a back spin put

00:06:32.370 --> 00:06:34.480
on it by the pitcher going up.

00:06:34.480 --> 00:06:36.640
Now, it's hard to
appreciate, but just look

00:06:36.640 --> 00:06:40.680
how straight the
left-hand image is.

00:06:40.680 --> 00:06:44.790
And then watch how much
curve the other pitch gets.

00:06:44.790 --> 00:06:49.300
Just appreciate the
curve on the one pitch

00:06:49.300 --> 00:06:50.960
and the straightness
on the other.

00:06:50.960 --> 00:06:53.442
So like any trained
engineer scientist,

00:06:53.442 --> 00:06:54.900
you should be
observing this thing,

00:06:54.900 --> 00:06:58.680
and your natural curiosity
would drive questions.

00:06:58.680 --> 00:06:59.595
What's going on here?

00:06:59.595 --> 00:07:01.970
These are two different pitches
with two different grips.

00:07:01.970 --> 00:07:05.004
Both are thrown over
98 miles an hour.

00:07:05.004 --> 00:07:06.920
Now, baseball fans might
know what that means,

00:07:06.920 --> 00:07:08.990
but these are
extremely fast pitches.

00:07:08.990 --> 00:07:12.510
One is rising against gravity.

00:07:12.510 --> 00:07:15.770
It's actually defying
gravity and going up.

00:07:15.770 --> 00:07:21.050
And the other is taking this
left to right turn so much so

00:07:21.050 --> 00:07:24.040
that the catcher
can't even catch it.

00:07:24.040 --> 00:07:27.770
The point is this
is just the time

00:07:27.770 --> 00:07:32.270
to observe and ask questions,
like any good investigation.

00:07:32.270 --> 00:07:35.270
Now, this is when Daniel
Bard was quite good.

00:07:35.270 --> 00:07:38.080
And he was getting people
out left and right.

00:07:38.080 --> 00:07:41.190
This pitch here to
the right was one

00:07:41.190 --> 00:07:44.530
of those-- we call them Bugs
Bunny pitches in baseball.

00:07:44.530 --> 00:07:46.780
It references the old
"Bugs Bunny" cartoon

00:07:46.780 --> 00:07:48.650
when you had crazy pitches.

00:07:48.650 --> 00:07:50.280
Now, this is real data.

00:07:50.280 --> 00:07:57.220
So here is a field of pitches
that are yellow triangles.

00:07:57.220 --> 00:08:01.520
You can sort of see them in
here behind the blue squares,

00:08:01.520 --> 00:08:02.760
which are the changeup.

00:08:02.760 --> 00:08:06.360
But this pitch right here--
these two pitches way over here

00:08:06.360 --> 00:08:08.270
to the left side of
that screen where

00:08:08.270 --> 00:08:12.650
the pitch was that pitch that
had that big break-- what

00:08:12.650 --> 00:08:14.400
you're seeing here is data.

00:08:14.400 --> 00:08:16.020
You're acting like
the catcher here.

00:08:16.020 --> 00:08:20.020
And this is where all
the pitches move relative

00:08:20.020 --> 00:08:21.090
to the bullet spin.

00:08:21.090 --> 00:08:23.960
The bullet spin is right in
the middle of the axis, right

00:08:23.960 --> 00:08:26.540
in the middle of the
two big axes there.

00:08:26.540 --> 00:08:27.790
That would be the bullet spin.

00:08:27.790 --> 00:08:31.600
The ball is just going along
its trajectory with gravity.

00:08:31.600 --> 00:08:33.870
But then you add the
spin that the pitcher

00:08:33.870 --> 00:08:37.750
can put on the ball, and you
get different types of pitches.

00:08:37.750 --> 00:08:39.870
So now, this is
Daniel Bard the good.

00:08:39.870 --> 00:08:44.730
This red cloud are his
fastballs that rise.

00:08:44.730 --> 00:08:46.820
The one you saw on the
left to Derek Jeter,

00:08:46.820 --> 00:08:48.810
that's the red cloud.

00:08:48.810 --> 00:08:52.240
Then buried in there
is the yellow cloud

00:08:52.240 --> 00:08:57.320
of triangles where he's
got that pitch that bends.

00:08:57.320 --> 00:09:00.090
Now, I'm going to show you--
this is when he's good.

00:09:00.090 --> 00:09:04.000
This Daniel Bard the good,
Daniel Bard the next year,

00:09:04.000 --> 00:09:06.040
and Daniel Bard the next year.

00:09:06.040 --> 00:09:09.908
And pretty much after
this, he's out of baseball.

00:09:09.908 --> 00:09:12.250
I'll at least scroll back.

00:09:12.250 --> 00:09:14.630
Daniel Bard the
good, Daniel Bard

00:09:14.630 --> 00:09:17.119
the next year, his last year.

00:09:17.119 --> 00:09:18.660
He's tried since
then, but he's never

00:09:18.660 --> 00:09:21.220
made really any
appearances since then

00:09:21.220 --> 00:09:22.830
in Major League Baseball.

00:09:22.830 --> 00:09:26.340
Now, if you follow the red
cloud, you'll see what I mean.

00:09:26.340 --> 00:09:28.480
This red cloud-- if
you can picture this,

00:09:28.480 --> 00:09:30.970
this is a catcher's orientation.

00:09:30.970 --> 00:09:36.970
This red cloud is balls that are
thrown by Daniel Bard that move

00:09:36.970 --> 00:09:39.750
a lot from that center point.

00:09:39.750 --> 00:09:41.680
If you pick where
that red cloud is,

00:09:41.680 --> 00:09:43.710
the center of that
red cloud, you

00:09:43.710 --> 00:09:48.770
can see it move as Daniel
Bard is going from good

00:09:48.770 --> 00:09:52.430
to mediocre-ish to not so good.

00:09:52.430 --> 00:09:54.070
And then he's out of the game.

00:09:54.070 --> 00:09:56.120
The point is this
is datasets that we

00:09:56.120 --> 00:09:59.620
can use to analyze
pitching performance,

00:09:59.620 --> 00:10:02.070
the movement of the baseball.

00:10:02.070 --> 00:10:04.810
So instead of just watching
video and making assessments

00:10:04.810 --> 00:10:07.350
of how well balls move,
we can measure now

00:10:07.350 --> 00:10:11.160
how the balls actually
move based on the spin put

00:10:11.160 --> 00:10:13.050
on the ball by the pitcher.

00:10:13.050 --> 00:10:17.540
So this is driving the
analytics in baseball.

00:10:17.540 --> 00:10:19.470
The decision making
in baseball can be

00:10:19.470 --> 00:10:21.910
based on this kind of data now.

00:10:21.910 --> 00:10:26.770
Now, this is older data--
older data as in 2007 and '8

00:10:26.770 --> 00:10:28.670
is when this dataset emerges.

00:10:28.670 --> 00:10:30.780
And it's done by video.

00:10:30.780 --> 00:10:34.710
Two video cameras are
trained between the area

00:10:34.710 --> 00:10:38.850
of the pitcher and the
catcher, and they basically

00:10:38.850 --> 00:10:43.700
do a triangulation of the
ball by video analytics,

00:10:43.700 --> 00:10:49.080
and then they reconfigure
the whole trajectory

00:10:49.080 --> 00:10:52.480
of the pitch, from the release
all the way to the catcher,

00:10:52.480 --> 00:10:53.820
just using video analytics.

00:10:53.820 --> 00:10:55.700
It's called PITCHf/x.

00:10:55.700 --> 00:10:57.680
Now, PITCHf/x is
really, really important

00:10:57.680 --> 00:10:59.380
to baseball analytics.

00:10:59.380 --> 00:11:01.420
We've actually moved on.

00:11:01.420 --> 00:11:02.750
But let's go back.

00:11:02.750 --> 00:11:05.330
We've just gone through a
simple little couple minutes

00:11:05.330 --> 00:11:09.330
exercise looking at Daniel Bard
the good, his actual video,

00:11:09.330 --> 00:11:12.820
some data showing how
his pitches might move,

00:11:12.820 --> 00:11:15.630
and how that might drive
some decision making.

00:11:15.630 --> 00:11:19.600
An objective look at
Daniel Bard's performance

00:11:19.600 --> 00:11:23.110
is what we can see with
this kind of dataset.

00:11:23.110 --> 00:11:25.990
So this goes to the
definition again.

00:11:25.990 --> 00:11:28.810
Voltaire was the one who
said first define your terms.

00:11:28.810 --> 00:11:32.080
Well, sabermetrics to me--
and I think most people

00:11:32.080 --> 00:11:35.360
who really are practitioners
would agree with this--

00:11:35.360 --> 00:11:37.510
it's the study of
the game of baseball

00:11:37.510 --> 00:11:40.390
through observation,
by looking carefully.

00:11:40.390 --> 00:11:42.130
Now, sometimes you
can do experiments,

00:11:42.130 --> 00:11:43.550
but usually you don't.

00:11:43.550 --> 00:11:45.450
It's more like
astronomy that way.

00:11:45.450 --> 00:11:47.246
You are observing
things and trying

00:11:47.246 --> 00:11:49.620
to figure out what's happening
through your observations.

00:11:49.620 --> 00:11:52.050
That's much more
what sabermetrics is.

00:11:52.050 --> 00:11:56.340
And here's the definition I
start off with all my courses.

00:11:56.340 --> 00:11:59.120
This is the simplified
version of sabermetrics--

00:11:59.120 --> 00:12:01.430
the scientific and
objective analysis

00:12:01.430 --> 00:12:04.080
of baseball-- much
more broadly defined

00:12:04.080 --> 00:12:06.270
than just looking at
the statistical analysis

00:12:06.270 --> 00:12:07.930
of baseball data.

00:12:07.930 --> 00:12:09.660
So this is an important
part to start.

00:12:09.660 --> 00:12:14.300
Baseball can be treated as
an observational science.

00:12:14.300 --> 00:12:16.680
You can start thinking
about the game

00:12:16.680 --> 00:12:19.340
and understanding it better.

00:12:19.340 --> 00:12:23.070
Now, what we've done
at BU and at edx.org

00:12:23.070 --> 00:12:26.990
is develop our course
called Sabermetrics 101:

00:12:26.990 --> 00:12:29.400
An Introduction to
Baseball Analytics.

00:12:29.400 --> 00:12:32.640
And this is one of
the big innovations

00:12:32.640 --> 00:12:34.220
we had in our course.

00:12:34.220 --> 00:12:35.570
The course is very successful.

00:12:35.570 --> 00:12:37.230
I could go on about
all the data points

00:12:37.230 --> 00:12:41.720
of why EdX loves this course,
and why BU loves this course,

00:12:41.720 --> 00:12:43.820
and why the students
have loved this course.

