00:13:07.620 --> 00:13:12.840
and we start doing SQL
queries using the SQL Sandbox.

00:13:12.840 --> 00:13:15.490
So it was an engineering
thing to build this little SQL

00:13:15.490 --> 00:13:16.030
Sandbox.

00:13:16.030 --> 00:13:17.940
It wasn't tricky,
but it really had

00:13:17.940 --> 00:13:19.410
to look right for the users.

00:13:19.410 --> 00:13:22.250
That was one of the
big innovations we had

00:13:22.250 --> 00:13:26.280
in this MOOC in the EdX course.

00:13:26.280 --> 00:13:30.130
This is a-- if you can see
this, this is a simple query,

00:13:30.130 --> 00:13:32.120
and you can see
some of the results.

00:13:32.120 --> 00:13:34.700
You basically run a
query, and you get

00:13:34.700 --> 00:13:36.250
a bunch of results in a table.

00:13:36.250 --> 00:13:39.460
And you can even push a button
to download the full results.

00:13:39.460 --> 00:13:42.110
In this case, this
query, I think,

00:13:42.110 --> 00:13:44.830
generated something
like 25,000 rows.

00:13:44.830 --> 00:13:49.490
These are different
sets of data for games

00:13:49.490 --> 00:13:51.670
between 2000 and 2009.

00:13:51.670 --> 00:13:56.460
So this was one innovation
that we found worked very well

00:13:56.460 --> 00:13:57.880
for our students.

00:13:57.880 --> 00:13:59.950
In addition, the thing
we innovated here

00:13:59.950 --> 00:14:01.630
was something called tracks.

00:14:01.630 --> 00:14:03.950
We realized in Introduction
to Data Analytics,

00:14:03.950 --> 00:14:06.000
we'd get some people who
were data scientists who

00:14:06.000 --> 00:14:07.867
were curious about baseball.

00:14:07.867 --> 00:14:09.450
We'd get some baseball
people who were

00:14:09.450 --> 00:14:11.440
curious about data science.

00:14:11.440 --> 00:14:14.560
And we'd get different folks
with different interests coming

00:14:14.560 --> 00:14:15.910
into this class.

00:14:15.910 --> 00:14:19.360
So we created tracks--
tracks of different topics.

00:14:19.360 --> 00:14:20.960
We created a sabermetrics track.

00:14:20.960 --> 00:14:23.360
It was a street baseball track.

00:14:23.360 --> 00:14:25.070
We created a
technical track, where

00:14:25.070 --> 00:14:27.910
we worked through SQL and
R, but a lot of our students

00:14:27.910 --> 00:14:31.910
already had that done, like
maybe many in this room.

00:14:31.910 --> 00:14:33.780
If they took this
course, they actually

00:14:33.780 --> 00:14:37.370
wouldn't have to take
the technical track.

00:14:37.370 --> 00:14:38.580
We also had a history track.

00:14:38.580 --> 00:14:40.230
We also had a statistics track.

00:14:40.230 --> 00:14:43.470
This didn't pretend
to be Statistics 101,

00:14:43.470 --> 00:14:45.990
but it did cover the
statistics needed

00:14:45.990 --> 00:14:50.070
to do basic analytics that
we required for the course.

00:14:50.070 --> 00:14:52.890
So the different tracks
was another innovation

00:14:52.890 --> 00:14:55.560
that actually many other
introductory courses on EdX

00:14:55.560 --> 00:14:57.170
have used since then.

00:14:57.170 --> 00:15:00.340
So that was a nice
innovation we also had.

00:15:00.340 --> 00:15:03.630
The last thing we had was
something called the Grader.

00:15:03.630 --> 00:15:09.190
We would take-- people would run
a SQL query for their problem

00:15:09.190 --> 00:15:12.252
set and submit the
dataset as their answer.

00:15:12.252 --> 00:15:13.710
And we had it in
a whole algorithm.

00:15:13.710 --> 00:15:17.090
We developed an algorithm
to try to grade each answer.

00:15:17.090 --> 00:15:19.190
It involved the right
number of columns, rows,

00:15:19.190 --> 00:15:21.620
the order of the
columns and the rows,

00:15:21.620 --> 00:15:24.350
and different criteria
to give different grades.

00:15:24.350 --> 00:15:27.550
But the Grader was another
innovation for the class.

00:15:27.550 --> 00:15:31.980
Now, in terms of baseball,
really, baseball--

00:15:31.980 --> 00:15:35.850
when we talk about sabermetrics,
we're modeling the game.

00:15:35.850 --> 00:15:38.580
Just like modeling any
system you want to model,

00:15:38.580 --> 00:15:40.990
you observe it carefully, and
you try to think about it.

00:15:40.990 --> 00:15:43.320
So when you think
about baseball,

00:15:43.320 --> 00:15:45.560
you try to understand
the game's about winning,

00:15:45.560 --> 00:15:46.880
but how do you win the game.

00:15:46.880 --> 00:15:49.540
You win the game with runs.

00:15:49.540 --> 00:15:53.180
So essentially, when you talk
about baseball analytics,

00:15:53.180 --> 00:15:56.360
you're talking about
analyzing runs.

00:15:56.360 --> 00:15:58.000
How are runs created?

00:15:58.000 --> 00:16:00.220
How are runs prevented?

00:16:00.220 --> 00:16:01.630
And that's the model.

00:16:01.630 --> 00:16:04.130
And that's the key--
that's the standard

00:16:04.130 --> 00:16:08.850
you develop as you build all
these models for baseball.

00:16:08.850 --> 00:16:11.650
Now, fundamentally, when
you think about runs--

00:16:11.650 --> 00:16:15.930
and baseball fans know this--
you think about great players.

00:16:15.930 --> 00:16:17.890
And they're going
to create runs.

00:16:17.890 --> 00:16:20.450
David Ortiz is a
great player, and he's

00:16:20.450 --> 00:16:23.170
got a great batting average
and lots of home runs.

00:16:23.170 --> 00:16:26.900
Well, very early on-- and I'm
talking a century ago-- very

00:16:26.900 --> 00:16:30.060
early on, people realized
the standard metrics

00:16:30.060 --> 00:16:34.392
for batting performance, batting
average, weren't working.

00:16:34.392 --> 00:16:36.100
There was a problem
with batting average,

00:16:36.100 --> 00:16:39.650
and people recognized
this a long time ago.

00:16:39.650 --> 00:16:44.070
This is a correlation
between team runs

00:16:44.070 --> 00:16:45.770
scored for a whole season.

00:16:45.770 --> 00:16:47.970
So you basically
take a team, you

00:16:47.970 --> 00:16:51.440
measure their runs
scored for that season,

00:16:51.440 --> 00:16:53.990
and you correlate it with
all their batting averages.

00:16:53.990 --> 00:16:56.250
Now, batting average
was the standard metric

00:16:56.250 --> 00:16:59.540
for hitting performance
for the longest time.

00:16:59.540 --> 00:17:02.802
But even 100 years ago, people
said this isn't good enough.

00:17:02.802 --> 00:17:06.900
And it actually has a
fairly low correlation.

00:17:06.900 --> 00:17:08.290
Not as bad as this graph.

00:17:08.290 --> 00:17:11.240
This is the graph I always
show when I do these talks,

00:17:11.240 --> 00:17:13.470
because it's got no correlation.

00:17:13.470 --> 00:17:16.250
Same x-axis-- team runs scored.

00:17:16.250 --> 00:17:20.560
Take any given team in a
season, count their runs scored.

00:17:20.560 --> 00:17:24.390
But then you try to plot it
against the number of outs

00:17:24.390 --> 00:17:25.872
they record on defense.

00:17:25.872 --> 00:17:27.900
Now, these should
not be correlated,

00:17:27.900 --> 00:17:32.170
because one is offense-- scoring
runs-- and one is defense,

00:17:32.170 --> 00:17:33.730
preventing runs.

00:17:33.730 --> 00:17:36.330
Now, if you do it
different ways,

00:17:36.330 --> 00:17:38.080
you can find correlations
with these data,

00:17:38.080 --> 00:17:40.660
but I chose it this way--
very low correlation.

00:17:40.660 --> 00:17:42.720
But I'll show you
the final graph.

00:17:42.720 --> 00:17:46.040
This is a higher correlation
for offensive performance.

00:17:46.040 --> 00:17:50.850
Now, this is a fundamental
concept in sabermetrics.

00:17:50.850 --> 00:17:52.310
This is what you do.

00:17:52.310 --> 00:17:53.820
You look at the game.

00:17:53.820 --> 00:17:55.650
You observe the game.

00:17:55.650 --> 00:17:58.200
You think about how
to model run scoring.

00:17:58.200 --> 00:18:01.330
Instead of using standard
metrics like batting average,

00:18:01.330 --> 00:18:04.670
you can take this very simple
metric-- this is actually

00:18:04.670 --> 00:18:06.710
quite a simple formula.

00:18:06.710 --> 00:18:11.990
This is just hits added
to walks, H plus BB.

00:18:11.990 --> 00:18:16.190
So just measure the team
hits and the team walks.

00:18:16.190 --> 00:18:18.530
You multiply it by
another component,

00:18:18.530 --> 00:18:22.080
which is total bases, which
adds up singles, doubles,

00:18:22.080 --> 00:18:26.010
triples, home runs,
a little formula,

00:18:26.010 --> 00:18:30.560
divided by the number
of at bats by walks.

00:18:30.560 --> 00:18:32.530
So this is a really
simple formula.

00:18:32.530 --> 00:18:36.100
But look how well it
correlates with run scoring.

00:18:36.100 --> 00:18:40.130
So this simple formula was
developed in the early '80s,

00:18:40.130 --> 00:18:42.120
'70s.

00:18:42.120 --> 00:18:49.070
And it really changed the
nature of baseball analytics.

00:18:49.070 --> 00:18:51.011
Because the analysts who
figured this out just

00:18:51.011 --> 00:18:52.260
did what I've just showed you.

00:18:52.260 --> 00:18:56.070
They said people for years have
been saying batting average is

00:18:56.070 --> 00:18:58.560
not a good metric for
offensive performance,

00:18:58.560 --> 00:19:00.340
for modeling the game,
for understanding

00:19:00.340 --> 00:19:02.630
the offensive
performance in baseball.

00:19:02.630 --> 00:19:04.270
But this is.

00:19:04.270 --> 00:19:06.630
Now, they kept saying
this over and over again

00:19:06.630 --> 00:19:09.670
since the early '80s,
and nothing changed.

00:19:09.670 --> 00:19:16.650
These were outsiders who had no
access to the actual clubhouse,

00:19:16.650 --> 00:19:18.180
to the decision makers.

00:19:18.180 --> 00:19:21.180
The decision makers weren't
listening to the folks

00:19:21.180 --> 00:19:23.630
telling everybody
there's a better way

00:19:23.630 --> 00:19:26.220
to model the game of baseball.

00:19:26.220 --> 00:19:29.110
And you can imagine the
market inefficiency.

00:19:29.110 --> 00:19:32.810
Instead of modeling your team
on the best batting average,

00:19:32.810 --> 00:19:34.990
the players with the
best batting average,

00:19:34.990 --> 00:19:37.870
you can start modeling
your team on the player

00:19:37.870 --> 00:19:39.180
with-- oh, I'm sorry.

00:19:39.180 --> 00:19:41.140
Sorry for the flashing slides.

00:19:41.140 --> 00:19:43.810
You can model your
team on the player who

00:19:43.810 --> 00:19:47.010
gets harder hit balls,
which is measured

00:19:47.010 --> 00:19:51.090
by the TB here, home runs
and triples and doubles,

00:19:51.090 --> 00:19:52.330
and get walks.

00:19:52.330 --> 00:19:53.460
Walks are added here.

00:19:53.460 --> 00:19:56.720
So this formula-- this really,
really simple formula--

00:19:56.720 --> 00:19:59.820
gets at another
level of modeling

00:19:59.820 --> 00:20:02.100
the game more accurately.

00:20:02.100 --> 00:20:04.010
And the market
inefficiency now is

00:20:04.010 --> 00:20:07.580
taking care of people who
hit home runs and triples

00:20:07.580 --> 00:20:10.360
and doubles and take walks.

00:20:10.360 --> 00:20:15.120
Now, this market inefficiency
is completely closed today.

00:20:15.120 --> 00:20:18.050
But before the publication
of "Moneyball,"

00:20:18.050 --> 00:20:21.359
this market inefficiency
was wide open.

00:20:21.359 --> 00:20:23.650
It was first described, like
I said, in the early '80s.

00:20:23.650 --> 00:20:28.660
But it took two
decades-- two decades--

00:20:28.660 --> 00:20:33.060
before you got that
little crack in the door

00:20:33.060 --> 00:20:35.332
into the clubhouse
to convince people

00:20:35.332 --> 00:20:37.540
that this is the way to
think about the game, the way

00:20:37.540 --> 00:20:39.050
to model the game.

00:20:39.050 --> 00:20:42.990
Now, today, fast forward another
decade since "Moneyball,"

00:20:42.990 --> 00:20:49.270
there are 150 analysts
on 30 teams who--

00:20:49.270 --> 00:20:51.990
this is what they grew up on.

00:20:51.990 --> 00:20:53.610
This is fundamental.

00:20:53.610 --> 00:20:57.320
This is like 2 plus 2 equals
4 to these 150 analysts.

00:20:57.320 --> 00:21:01.930
We're talking about a dramatic
paradigm shift in an industry.

00:21:01.930 --> 00:21:03.500
Now, this is just entertainment.

00:21:03.500 --> 00:21:04.710
We understand that.

00:21:04.710 --> 00:21:07.590
But it's a dramatic paradigm
shift in this industry.

00:21:07.590 --> 00:21:11.160
This is the importance
of baseball analytics

00:21:11.160 --> 00:21:14.900
as an emerging-- discipline
may be too strong,

00:21:14.900 --> 00:21:18.800
but it's certainly an emerging
area of study for folks

00:21:18.800 --> 00:21:21.770
who want to do
this kind of work.

00:21:21.770 --> 00:21:25.560
It's essentially
interesting data science

00:21:25.560 --> 00:21:26.760
around entertainment.

00:21:26.760 --> 00:21:30.850
So let's go back to
another set of data.

00:21:30.850 --> 00:21:33.470
Another set of data
emerged in 2008.

00:21:33.470 --> 00:21:38.747
This is Jon Lester
from 2007 to 2014.

00:21:38.747 --> 00:21:39.830
These are all his pitches.

00:21:39.830 --> 00:21:41.750
Now, remember what
this is again.

00:21:41.750 --> 00:21:44.090
I'm going to try to
describe this carefully.

00:21:44.090 --> 00:21:46.430
This is the catcher view.

00:21:46.430 --> 00:21:47.640
You're the catcher.

00:21:47.640 --> 00:21:48.982
So Jon Lester is the pitcher.

00:21:48.982 --> 00:21:50.940
And he's throwing-- he's
a left-handed pitcher,

00:21:50.940 --> 00:21:53.720
and he's throwing pitches
to you, the catcher.

00:21:53.720 --> 00:21:56.780
And he's got five
different pitches.

00:21:56.780 --> 00:22:00.140
The four seam
fastball is the one

00:22:00.140 --> 00:22:01.430
that's going to rise the most.

00:22:01.430 --> 00:22:04.860
So that cloud of black
circles is the one

00:22:04.860 --> 00:22:09.120
that's the highest velocity.

00:22:09.120 --> 00:22:11.280
That's the fastest pitch.

00:22:11.280 --> 00:22:15.100
Now, you can see he's got
balls that-- the sinker,

00:22:15.100 --> 00:22:18.039
this gray cloud
here, that actually

00:22:18.039 --> 00:22:19.830
moves a little different
than the fastball.

00:22:19.830 --> 00:22:22.780
These are the two pitches
you saw by Daniel Bard.

00:22:22.780 --> 00:22:25.410
The fastball was the one
on the left to Derek Jeter

00:22:25.410 --> 00:22:28.360
by Daniel Bard, and the
sinker was the one that

00:22:28.360 --> 00:22:31.130
curved so much left to right.

00:22:31.130 --> 00:22:34.200
Now, for Jon Lester, he's
a left-handed pitcher.

00:22:34.200 --> 00:22:36.120
It's going to curve
the other way.

00:22:36.120 --> 00:22:38.830
It's going to curve from right
to left, because he's lefty.

00:22:38.830 --> 00:22:40.710
So when he throws his
two-seamed sinker,

00:22:40.710 --> 00:22:42.490
it's going to move this way.

00:22:42.490 --> 00:22:44.430
Now, he's got three
other pitches.

00:22:44.430 --> 00:22:47.830
He's got his curveball,
which is going to spin down.

00:22:47.830 --> 00:22:50.510
And that's the
yellow cloud here.

00:22:50.510 --> 00:22:53.950
He's got the changeup, which is
a whole other pitch altogether.

00:22:53.950 --> 00:22:55.280
It's meant to slow down.

00:22:55.280 --> 00:22:57.120
You can see how it's
lower on the graph.

00:22:57.120 --> 00:22:59.850
It's a lower velocity pitch.

00:22:59.850 --> 00:23:03.547
So he grips it differently, and
it's actually a slower pitch.

00:23:03.547 --> 00:23:05.630
And then he's got another
pitch that he's spinning

00:23:05.630 --> 00:23:08.470
the other way from the sinker.

00:23:08.470 --> 00:23:10.170
He calls it a cutter, a slider.

00:23:10.170 --> 00:23:12.850
These are different names
for very similar pitches

00:23:12.850 --> 00:23:16.800
that go the different way
than the classic sinker pitch.

00:23:16.800 --> 00:23:19.360
The point is-- if you don't
know baseball, that's fine.

00:23:19.360 --> 00:23:22.950
The point is there's a pitcher
grabbing a baseball that's

00:23:22.950 --> 00:23:26.970
going to spin in air, and
he's doing this on purpose.

00:23:26.970 --> 00:23:30.160
So we can collect all these
data and look at Jon Lester.

00:23:30.160 --> 00:23:34.210
Now, one data point of one
pitcher doesn't matter much.

00:23:34.210 --> 00:23:36.510
But if we compare Jon
Lester now to another?

00:23:36.510 --> 00:23:38.530
This is another
left-handed pitcher

00:23:38.530 --> 00:23:42.860
with the same
five-pitch repertoire.

00:23:42.860 --> 00:23:44.020
This is Jose Quintana.

00:23:44.020 --> 00:23:48.090
Now, what I've done is
I've manipulated the images

00:23:48.090 --> 00:23:49.440
so the scales are the same.

00:23:49.440 --> 00:23:51.940
And I'm going to
go back and forth.

00:23:51.940 --> 00:23:55.410
Now, you should understand
that one pitcher is throwing it

00:23:55.410 --> 00:24:01.620
faster, and one pitcher is
throwing it with more movement.

00:24:01.620 --> 00:24:04.950
And this is the way now
to measure pitching.

00:24:04.950 --> 00:24:07.010
We're not going to
measure ERA anymore,

00:24:07.010 --> 00:24:10.200
which is a fundamental measure
of pitching performance.

00:24:10.200 --> 00:24:14.280
Now we can take these data and
say who moves the ball better.

00:24:14.280 --> 00:24:16.260
Who moves the ball faster?

00:24:16.260 --> 00:24:20.450
Now, there's a key piece missing
here in this dataset right

00:24:20.450 --> 00:24:24.054
here, which is how
accurately they can throw it,

00:24:24.054 --> 00:24:26.220
their placement of the
pitches over the strike zone.

00:24:26.220 --> 00:24:29.690
But just on the skill set
of these two pitchers here,

00:24:29.690 --> 00:24:33.620
Lester has more velocity and
more movement of these pitches.

00:24:33.620 --> 00:24:36.720
These scales are
exactly the same.

00:24:36.720 --> 00:24:38.840
And so now this is
just to show you

00:24:38.840 --> 00:24:42.490
we have another way to
measure pitching performance

00:24:42.490 --> 00:24:45.900
using technology and new data.

00:24:45.900 --> 00:24:48.630
So this is using to
PITCHf/x dataset,

00:24:48.630 --> 00:24:51.220
and understanding the
different pitch types,

00:24:51.220 --> 00:24:55.210
and understanding how these
pitches move as a measurement

00:24:55.210 --> 00:24:57.270
of value of pitchers.

00:24:57.270 --> 00:25:01.480
Now, I throw this one in
here just because it's fun.

00:25:01.480 --> 00:25:04.870
Has anyone ever
seen this before?

00:25:04.870 --> 00:25:05.920
This is Todd Frazier.

00:25:05.920 --> 00:25:08.650
Todd Frazier now actually plays
for the Chicago White Sox.

00:25:08.650 --> 00:25:10.700
This is when he was on the Reds.

00:25:10.700 --> 00:25:12.320
If anyone is from
New Jersey, he's

00:25:12.320 --> 00:25:14.400
from Point Pleasant, New Jersey.

00:25:14.400 --> 00:25:15.450
New Jersey Shore?

00:25:15.450 --> 00:25:16.319
No one?

00:25:16.319 --> 00:25:16.860
Jersey Shore?

00:25:16.860 --> 00:25:18.500
OK, fine.

00:25:18.500 --> 00:25:19.430
But watch.

00:25:19.430 --> 00:25:24.160
If you look carefully, it's
pretty obvious his right hand--

00:25:24.160 --> 00:25:29.790
watch his right hand-- is off
the bat at bat-ball contact.

00:25:29.790 --> 00:25:32.810
But if you look carefully,
his left hand is, too.

00:25:32.810 --> 00:25:38.210
He has essentially thrown
the bat at the ball.

00:25:38.210 --> 00:25:41.100
He's throwing the
bat at the ball.

00:25:41.100 --> 00:25:42.870
Now, if you've ever
played baseball,

00:25:42.870 --> 00:25:46.036
the coach would never
tell you to do this.

00:25:46.036 --> 00:25:49.230
This is not classic baseball.

00:25:49.230 --> 00:25:53.110
But what's really interesting
here is the physics.

00:25:53.110 --> 00:25:54.890
We can use this as
a physics example

00:25:54.890 --> 00:26:00.080
of understanding bat-ball
contact, the mechanics of this.

00:26:00.080 --> 00:26:03.750
But beyond that,
this was a home run.

00:26:03.750 --> 00:26:08.180
He hit this ball
about-- over 400 feet.

