00:27:12.140 --> 00:27:13.750
Now, here's another dataset.

00:27:13.750 --> 00:27:16.730
This is actually
really interesting.

00:27:16.730 --> 00:27:21.420
This is using-- this
is by Greg Rybarcyzk.

00:27:21.420 --> 00:27:23.810
He's actually a Red
Sox analyst now.

00:27:23.810 --> 00:27:28.650
What he did is took video of
every home run ever played.

00:27:28.650 --> 00:27:32.940
He had a package, and he could
watch videos of all games.

00:27:32.940 --> 00:27:37.946
And he would find every video
of a home run since 2006.

00:27:37.946 --> 00:27:39.570
So this is yeoman
work, because there's

00:27:39.570 --> 00:27:42.390
about 5,000 home runs a year.

00:27:42.390 --> 00:27:46.350
And he would find where
it landed in the ballpark.

00:27:46.350 --> 00:27:51.100
And he had 3D reconstructions
digitally, reconstructions

00:27:51.100 --> 00:27:52.770
of all ballparks.

00:27:52.770 --> 00:27:57.360
And he would time on his
video bat-ball contact

00:27:57.360 --> 00:27:58.950
and then where it landed.

00:27:58.950 --> 00:28:04.620
So he has a time in the air,
a position where it landed.

00:28:04.620 --> 00:28:07.190
And he actually got more
sophisticated near the end

00:28:07.190 --> 00:28:10.150
and put in weather in there,
and he put in wind in there.

00:28:10.150 --> 00:28:14.030
He talked to the physicists
about batted ball flight,

00:28:14.030 --> 00:28:16.400
understood better about
the potential batted ball

00:28:16.400 --> 00:28:19.850
flight moves here that are
typical for righty lefty, lefty

00:28:19.850 --> 00:28:21.150
righty stuff.

00:28:21.150 --> 00:28:24.770
And he modeled
various components.

00:28:24.770 --> 00:28:29.760
So this dataset is just
looking at home runs in 2009.

00:28:29.760 --> 00:28:35.340
So this is the cloud of all home
runs graphing their batted ball

00:28:35.340 --> 00:28:38.160
velocity, how hard
the ball was hit.

00:28:38.160 --> 00:28:40.660
Now, Greg calculated this.

00:28:40.660 --> 00:28:43.140
He calculated the
batted ball velocity

00:28:43.140 --> 00:28:47.340
based on hang time in
the air and the distance

00:28:47.340 --> 00:28:49.480
and a few other parameters.

00:28:49.480 --> 00:28:52.810
He also determined
the launch angle.

00:28:52.810 --> 00:28:59.130
So he is estimating both launch
angle and batted ball velocity

00:28:59.130 --> 00:29:01.750
just by looking at video.

00:29:01.750 --> 00:29:04.410
Lot of work, but
probably a big error

00:29:04.410 --> 00:29:06.410
bar around the precision
of what this actually

00:29:06.410 --> 00:29:10.170
is, because he's doing
a lot of formulation

00:29:10.170 --> 00:29:12.250
to get these two
sets of numbers.

00:29:12.250 --> 00:29:14.600
But clearly, it should
show you something.

00:29:14.600 --> 00:29:16.290
What's the average?

00:29:16.290 --> 00:29:18.040
He's not too far off.

00:29:18.040 --> 00:29:20.380
This is pretty good modeling.

00:29:20.380 --> 00:29:24.130
But it tells you the
average batted ball velocity

00:29:24.130 --> 00:29:30.680
for a home run is about
103.6 miles per hour.

00:29:30.680 --> 00:29:34.240
Off the bat, home
runs average this.

00:29:34.240 --> 00:29:35.290
Now, there's a big range.

00:29:35.290 --> 00:29:38.730
You can see some home runs
were pretty weakly hit.

00:29:38.730 --> 00:29:41.670
Those are probably
things like pop ups

00:29:41.670 --> 00:29:45.990
at Fenway Park that scrape
the foul pole or something.

00:29:45.990 --> 00:29:48.590
So it's a weak hit that
might just be a home run.

00:29:48.590 --> 00:29:50.800
But some were hit quite hard.

00:29:50.800 --> 00:29:53.247
You can see the
outliers on both sides.

00:29:53.247 --> 00:29:54.830
And then you can see
the launch angle.

00:29:54.830 --> 00:29:56.810
Most people, when they
think about trajectories

00:29:56.810 --> 00:29:58.460
that you learn in
Mechanics 101, you

00:29:58.460 --> 00:30:00.140
think 45 degrees is the best.

00:30:00.140 --> 00:30:02.090
Well, in baseball, it's not.

00:30:02.090 --> 00:30:08.100
Data clearly shows you here
the launch angle is about 28.

00:30:08.100 --> 00:30:14.190
Now, the range is anywhere
from 43 down to 18 or 19.

00:30:14.190 --> 00:30:16.730
When you're hitting an
18 or 19 launch angle,

00:30:16.730 --> 00:30:18.000
that's a line drive.

00:30:18.000 --> 00:30:19.970
That's a low trajectory.

00:30:19.970 --> 00:30:23.430
And then, of course, you've
got the almost 45-degree

00:30:23.430 --> 00:30:24.610
trajectories.

00:30:24.610 --> 00:30:28.562
But the typical home run is
much more like 30 degrees.

00:30:28.562 --> 00:30:30.270
Now, this makes sense
when you understand

00:30:30.270 --> 00:30:33.290
the physics in the
backspin of a baseball

00:30:33.290 --> 00:30:37.620
and how balls move
in the fluid of air.

00:30:37.620 --> 00:30:40.560
So you can explain this
by looking at the science

00:30:40.560 --> 00:30:42.050
quite easily.

00:30:42.050 --> 00:30:45.130
But this was an important
little dataset to understand.

00:30:45.130 --> 00:30:47.470
Most people wouldn't
get this right away.

00:30:47.470 --> 00:30:51.660
Now, also in 2009, we
have another data set

00:30:51.660 --> 00:30:53.570
that looks at all
batted ball events.

00:30:53.570 --> 00:30:55.630
This is just April 2009.

00:30:55.630 --> 00:30:59.320
But it's another technology
just using video analytics.

00:30:59.320 --> 00:31:02.330
Remember that video
analytics of PITCHf/x

00:31:02.330 --> 00:31:05.640
where you basically
reconstruct the trajectory

00:31:05.640 --> 00:31:08.250
of the pitch with
high speed cameras

00:31:08.250 --> 00:31:12.660
in this area between the
pitcher's mound and home plate?

00:31:12.660 --> 00:31:14.850
You can do the same thing
with the batted ball.

00:31:14.850 --> 00:31:18.820
When the ball is hit, you
can watch the trajectory

00:31:18.820 --> 00:31:21.710
through those camera areas.

00:31:21.710 --> 00:31:24.020
Now, it wasn't a
great technology.

00:31:24.020 --> 00:31:26.030
It actually had lots of errors.

00:31:26.030 --> 00:31:29.820
But this dataset tells
us a very similar thing.

00:31:29.820 --> 00:31:32.060
What we're showing here
in different colors

00:31:32.060 --> 00:31:37.370
is a fly out, which is
a ball hit in the air.

00:31:37.370 --> 00:31:39.090
That's different
than a pop up, which

00:31:39.090 --> 00:31:40.650
is a ball hit in
the air which is

00:31:40.650 --> 00:31:43.580
closer to where the batter is.

00:31:43.580 --> 00:31:46.100
Then there's line outs and
ground outs and singles,

00:31:46.100 --> 00:31:47.290
doubles, and triples.

00:31:47.290 --> 00:31:48.870
For those of you
who know the game,

00:31:48.870 --> 00:31:50.700
you understand these clearly.

00:31:50.700 --> 00:31:53.590
But you can see where
these clouds are.

00:31:53.590 --> 00:31:57.065
I've reduced this cloud
into different points,

00:31:57.065 --> 00:32:00.380
the average points for
each of those eight events.

00:32:00.380 --> 00:32:04.000
These are the outs-- the pop
out, the fly out, the line out.

00:32:04.000 --> 00:32:06.510
And if you understand
the graph here looking

00:32:06.510 --> 00:32:09.220
at the velocity versus
the launch angle, which

00:32:09.220 --> 00:32:12.010
is what we showed before
