And you just can't call
errors on certain plays.

00:54:05.490 --> 00:54:12.050
If they're making ordinary
effort and they screw up,

00:54:12.050 --> 00:54:13.300
that's when you give an error.

00:54:13.300 --> 00:54:16.210
But if it's some crazy
thing that happened,

00:54:16.210 --> 00:54:18.362
that's-- you can't
give errors to that.

00:54:18.362 --> 00:54:19.820
AUDIENCE: Even when
they fall over.

00:54:19.820 --> 00:54:22.880
But they fell over not within
five feet of the ball, so--

00:54:25.390 --> 00:54:26.890
ANDY ANDRES: This
is being recorded,

00:54:26.890 --> 00:54:28.460
so I better watch what I say.

00:54:28.460 --> 00:54:33.410
But I have a lot of stories
about how the sausage is

00:54:33.410 --> 00:54:36.780
made in official scoring.

00:54:36.780 --> 00:54:39.380
AUDIENCE: The data you were
talking about collecting,

00:54:39.380 --> 00:54:41.180
is that available to
all the teams equally,

00:54:41.180 --> 00:54:42.680
or do some of them
have private data

00:54:42.680 --> 00:54:45.628
that they're adding into this?

00:54:45.628 --> 00:54:49.430
ANDY ANDRES: This dataset
is for every team.

00:54:49.430 --> 00:54:51.560
Every team has access to it.

00:54:51.560 --> 00:54:53.060
But that doesn't
mean other teams

00:54:53.060 --> 00:54:54.720
aren't adding their own data.

00:54:54.720 --> 00:54:56.470
There's other data
providers out there

00:54:56.470 --> 00:54:58.910
that are trying to
sell data to teams.

00:54:58.910 --> 00:55:01.210
And some teams buy it.

00:55:01.210 --> 00:55:05.970
Some teams are thinking about
data a little differently.

00:55:05.970 --> 00:55:07.270
They're gathering data.

00:55:07.270 --> 00:55:08.760
They're spending
money to get data

00:55:08.760 --> 00:55:10.860
in low minors and
other places, too.

00:55:10.860 --> 00:55:12.900
So each team is a
little different.

00:55:12.900 --> 00:55:17.540
But this dataset using
radar and video analytics

00:55:17.540 --> 00:55:20.850
is open to all 30 teams.

00:55:20.850 --> 00:55:23.840
AUDIENCE: So when
academics discover things,

00:55:23.840 --> 00:55:26.250
they publish them.

00:55:26.250 --> 00:55:31.180
In this case, finding a new
metric that works really

00:55:31.180 --> 00:55:35.710
well is probably something
you want to keep proprietary.

00:55:35.710 --> 00:55:37.660
Do you guys lean more
towards that or more

00:55:37.660 --> 00:55:40.360
towards sharing with each other?

00:55:40.360 --> 00:55:43.990
ANDY ANDRES: I think
the industry is always

00:55:43.990 --> 00:55:46.180
looking for the
market inefficiency

00:55:46.180 --> 00:55:48.660
and for that advantage.

00:55:48.660 --> 00:55:51.370
Now, this isn't a
clear cut advantage

00:55:51.370 --> 00:55:53.850
as some other industries.

00:55:53.850 --> 00:55:56.710
If you make a better widget
and you cut the price in half,

00:55:56.710 --> 00:55:58.580
you will make more money.

00:55:58.580 --> 00:56:00.942
That's a measure of that system.

00:56:00.942 --> 00:56:02.900
In this system, you want
to measure it by, say,

00:56:02.900 --> 00:56:05.890
World Series victories.

00:56:05.890 --> 00:56:10.880
Getting more value from your
players because of some metric

00:56:10.880 --> 00:56:13.980
about how hard
they hit the ball,

00:56:13.980 --> 00:56:17.430
that doesn't guarantee
a World Series victory.

00:56:17.430 --> 00:56:21.456
But it certainly would
be a slight improvement.

00:56:24.170 --> 00:56:26.390
And it is a market inefficiency.

00:56:26.390 --> 00:56:28.400
In terms of academics
and publishing,

00:56:28.400 --> 00:56:31.719
I think there is
the outside world--

00:56:31.719 --> 00:56:33.760
and I'm actually part of
the outside world, where

00:56:33.760 --> 00:56:35.600
we actually look
at data and we try

00:56:35.600 --> 00:56:39.630
to analyze it and publish it on
the web so everyone can see it.

00:56:39.630 --> 00:56:43.110
Then there's other data
involved and better models

00:56:43.110 --> 00:56:46.530
involved because of the
richer datasets in the clubs.

00:56:46.530 --> 00:56:48.720
And that's not something
we're privy to.

00:56:48.720 --> 00:56:50.190
The outside doesn't see that.

00:56:50.190 --> 00:56:52.390
It's very proprietary.

00:56:52.390 --> 00:56:54.970
There's some cross-talk
between teams, but not much.

00:56:54.970 --> 00:57:00.750
They usually hold information
pretty close to the vest.

00:57:00.750 --> 00:57:01.940
But I'm on the outside.

00:57:01.940 --> 00:57:10.096
So I just try to look at data
that I can find and analyze it.

00:57:15.084 --> 00:57:16.500
AUDIENCE: Two
questions, actually.

00:57:16.500 --> 00:57:22.310
So at the player level,
how much are teams

00:57:22.310 --> 00:57:24.840
sharing any data points?

00:57:24.840 --> 00:57:27.570
So one thing that
stood out was you

00:57:27.570 --> 00:57:29.570
said they put the
shift for Ortiz,

00:57:29.570 --> 00:57:31.280
but he hits to the middle.

00:57:31.280 --> 00:57:33.840
Do they share that with
their players at all

00:57:33.840 --> 00:57:37.820
and say, hey, you shouldn't
necessarily shift,

00:57:37.820 --> 00:57:40.490
and build in a
player-by-player strategy?

00:57:40.490 --> 00:57:41.400
Are teams doing that?

00:57:41.400 --> 00:57:43.510
ANDY ANDRES: Yes, absolutely.

00:57:43.510 --> 00:57:46.080
If you watch baseball
a lot, you'll

00:57:46.080 --> 00:57:52.110
see how every at bat
shifts the defense.

00:57:52.110 --> 00:57:53.580
Every new batter
coming up, they'll

00:57:53.580 --> 00:57:55.020
always have a different move.

00:57:55.020 --> 00:57:57.327
Even within pitch
counts, they'll shift.

00:57:57.327 --> 00:57:59.160
They'll move players
around in pitch counts.

00:57:59.160 --> 00:58:01.590
And so they understand
the different pitch counts

00:58:01.590 --> 00:58:04.310
and the batters impact where
you should be on defense.

00:58:04.310 --> 00:58:04.810
It's that.

00:58:04.810 --> 00:58:07.726
Granular.

00:58:07.726 --> 00:58:08.700
AUDIENCE: Cool.

00:58:08.700 --> 00:58:10.005
That's pretty interesting.

00:58:10.005 --> 00:58:10.880
ANDY ANDRES: I agree.

00:58:10.880 --> 00:58:12.600
AUDIENCE: And then
the other question I

00:58:12.600 --> 00:58:15.560
had was it seems
like this would be

00:58:15.560 --> 00:58:19.750
