00:59:00.350 --> 00:59:02.135
And these data are out there.

00:59:06.890 --> 00:59:10.600
AUDIENCE: When I saw the graphs
about Daniel Bard's pitching,

00:59:10.600 --> 00:59:12.517
two things jumped out
at me, and I wasn't sure

00:59:12.517 --> 00:59:13.724
if you had a comment on them.

00:59:13.724 --> 00:59:15.675
One, there's this old
thought that command

00:59:15.675 --> 00:59:18.109
is everything for a pitcher.

00:59:18.109 --> 00:59:19.650
If you don't have
command, it doesn't

00:59:19.650 --> 00:59:21.400
matter how fast you throw,
and if you have command,

00:59:21.400 --> 00:59:22.066
you can do well.

00:59:22.066 --> 00:59:24.080
And then there's
the other one, which

00:59:24.080 --> 00:59:28.340
is that it's all about
variance-- so if you lose

00:59:28.340 --> 00:59:30.232
fastball velocity
but your changeup

00:59:30.232 --> 00:59:32.690
can still be overpowering if
your changeup also slows down,

00:59:32.690 --> 00:59:36.090
like Keith Foulke
or Trevor Hoffman.

00:59:36.090 --> 00:59:39.010
But when I look at that graph,
one thing seems to hold up,

00:59:39.010 --> 00:59:40.320
and the other one doesn't.

00:59:40.320 --> 00:59:43.460
And I'm not sure if you
had a comment on that.

00:59:43.460 --> 00:59:43.960
Because he--

00:59:43.960 --> 00:59:44.940
ANDY ANDRES: On Daniel Bard?

00:59:44.940 --> 00:59:45.110
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:59:45.110 --> 00:59:47.320
Because he seemed to
retain a lot of variance

00:59:47.320 --> 00:59:51.686
from 2009 to 2011, but he
clearly lost almost all

00:59:51.686 --> 00:59:52.310
of his command.

00:59:54.900 --> 00:59:57.230
ANDY ANDRES: The observation
is he lost his command.

00:59:57.230 --> 00:59:59.840
If you watch what he did, he
just started walking batters

00:59:59.840 --> 01:00:00.660
everywhere.

01:00:00.660 --> 01:00:03.280
But that's not what this
dataset actually shows.

01:00:03.280 --> 01:00:04.930
So what this is
trying to represent

01:00:04.930 --> 01:00:07.790
is the movement of the pitches.

01:00:07.790 --> 01:00:10.300
And that's his
ability to spin it.

01:00:10.300 --> 01:00:12.870
AUDIENCE: But command is--
when you're a pitcher,

01:00:12.870 --> 01:00:16.040
you're expecting the ball
to behave a certain way.

01:00:16.040 --> 01:00:18.630
When I look at a graph like
this and I see a tight cluster,

01:00:18.630 --> 01:00:20.280
it means that the
pitch is predictable.

01:00:20.280 --> 01:00:22.650
And so the pitcher
can command the pitch

01:00:22.650 --> 01:00:25.490
by assuming that it's
going to go a certain way.

01:00:25.490 --> 01:00:27.840
And then if you go
two slides ahead,

01:00:27.840 --> 01:00:31.800
as the fastball graphs
start to spread out,

01:00:31.800 --> 01:00:33.460
it means that he's
walking players.

01:00:33.460 --> 01:00:34.630
He's lost command.

01:00:34.630 --> 01:00:36.520
But he still has a
lot of variation.

01:00:36.520 --> 01:00:40.440
His slider is actually breaking
even more than it was before.

01:00:40.440 --> 01:00:42.580
ANDY ANDRES: I think
this is not representing

01:00:42.580 --> 01:00:44.320
the strike zone and command.

01:00:44.320 --> 01:00:47.010
I could do another graph
which shows you how well he's

01:00:47.010 --> 01:00:49.450
hitting his spots.

01:00:49.450 --> 01:00:53.340
This is a measure of
movement of the pitch.

01:00:53.340 --> 01:00:57.120
So we're not really getting
is he hitting his spots.

01:00:57.120 --> 01:00:58.260
So you're right.

01:00:58.260 --> 01:01:00.070
If I were getting at
command another way,

01:01:00.070 --> 01:01:02.360
I'd look at how
well he's clustering

01:01:02.360 --> 01:01:07.020
around a certain band where
I want the pitches to go.

01:01:07.020 --> 01:01:09.550
But you mentioned
something really important.

01:01:09.550 --> 01:01:12.590
You mentioned this
idea of sequencing,

01:01:12.590 --> 01:01:16.290
the idea of not
being consistent, not

01:01:16.290 --> 01:01:18.270
showing the same thing.

01:01:18.270 --> 01:01:23.110
Advanced analytics today--
and there's real teams who

01:01:23.110 --> 01:01:27.190
understand this that
others don't-- this idea

01:01:27.190 --> 01:01:30.680
of sequencing, this
idea of understanding

01:01:30.680 --> 01:01:34.560
a pitcher-catcher-- being
in sync about a certain set

01:01:34.560 --> 01:01:38.250
of pitches, different kinds
of pitches, different pitches,

01:01:38.250 --> 01:01:41.460
different locations to different
batters and how that's working.

01:01:41.460 --> 01:01:45.020
So sequencing is really
important-- really,

01:01:45.020 --> 01:01:46.270
really important.

01:01:46.270 --> 01:01:49.800
This graph is showing more
his ability to spin the pitch.

01:01:49.800 --> 01:01:53.890
Something happened to
Daniel Bard after 2010.

01:01:53.890 --> 01:01:57.920
And it's sort of a mystery,
because he had such talent.

01:01:57.920 --> 01:01:59.090
It wasn't age.

01:01:59.090 --> 01:02:01.400
It wasn't injury.

01:02:01.400 --> 01:02:04.410
Something happened where he
just couldn't spin it as well.

01:02:04.410 --> 01:02:06.020
He couldn't spin
the pitches as well.

01:02:06.020 --> 01:02:07.800
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE]

01:02:07.800 --> 01:02:10.940
ANDY ANDRES: Yes, 2012
he started to start.

01:02:10.940 --> 01:02:12.850
But it was actually his choice.

01:02:12.850 --> 01:02:15.680
If you go back and look
it up, he wanted to start.

01:02:18.970 --> 01:02:21.200
Very interesting scenario here.

01:02:21.200 --> 01:02:23.270
Daniel Bard is--
someone is going

01:02:23.270 --> 01:02:26.780
to write a great book
about Daniel Bard someday.

01:02:26.780 --> 01:02:28.830
Maybe one of you.

